{"id":"2201.01562","submitter":"Wen-Qiang Liu","authors":"Wen-Qiang Liu and Zhang-qi Yin","title":"Efficiently calculating the work distribution of identical bosons with\n  boson sampling","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Boson sampling has been theoretically proposed and experimentally realized to\nexhibit quantum computational advantages. However, it still lacks the deep\nunderstanding of the practical applications of boson sampling. Here we propose\nto use boson sampling to efficiently calculate the work distribution of\nmultiple identical bosons in a one-dimensional piston system, which cannot be\ncalculated efficiently via classical computer. We numerically simulate the\ntransition amplitude betweenthe multi-boson eigenstates and obtain the\namplitude matrix. The matrix can be mapped to aprogrammable linear optical\nnetwork in a boson sampling machine, and the transition probability is directly\nestimated by counting the output photon distribution. As an example, we design\na concrete scheme to calculate the work distribution with programmable boson\nsampling experiments. Our results present a resource cost at polynomial\nhierarchy and bridge a benchmark for routing to the calculation of more complex\nwork distribution using only photons and linear optical elements.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 5 Jan 2022 12:08:55 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 11 Feb 2022 13:01:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-02-14"}
{"id":"2201.01563","submitter":"Zhi Zhou","authors":"Zhengqi Zhang, Zhidong Zhang, Zhi Zhou","title":"Identification of potential in diffusion equations from terminal\n  observation: analysis and discrete approximation","comments":"23 pages, 21 Figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA cs.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The aim of this paper is to study the recovery of a spatially dependent\npotential in a (sub)diffusion equation from overposed final time data. We\nconstruct a monotone operator one of whose fixed points is the unknown\npotential. The uniqueness of the identification is theoretically verified by\nusing the monotonicity of the operator and a fixed point argument. Moreover, we\nshow a conditional stability in Hilbert spaces under some suitable conditions\non the problem data. Next, a completely discrete scheme is developed, by using\nGalerkin finite element method in space and finite difference method in time,\nand then a fixed point iteration is applied to reconstruct the potential. We\nprove the linear convergence of the iterative algorithm by the contraction\nmapping theorem, and present a thorough error analysis for the reconstructed\npotential. Our derived \\textsl{a priori} error estimate provides a guideline to\nchoose discretization parameters according to the noise level. The analysis\nrelies heavily on some suitable nonstandard error estimates for the direct\nproblem as well as the aforementioned conditional stability. Numerical\nexperiments are provided to illustrate and complement our theoretical analysis.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 5 Jan 2022 12:09:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-01-06"}
